responses.content: Outstanding quarter with record revenue ($9.2B, +36% YoY) and profitability. Broad-based demand across Data Center AI, Server, and PC businesses. Free cash flow tripled.
Revenue $4.3B (+22% YoY). Server CPU revenue all-time high; Turin ramping rapidly. Instinct GPU business accelerating with MI350 ramp. MI300 deployments broadening.
Announced partnership with OpenAI to deploy 6 GW of Instinct GPUs (starting with MI450 in 2H 2026). Helios rack scale platform progressing. MI400 series on track for 2026.
Revenue $4.0B (+73% YoY). Record Client sales driven by Ryzen 9000. Gaming up significantly (+181% YoY) due to semi-custom seasonality and Radeon demand.
Revenue $9.2B (+36% YoY). Gross margin 54% (+40 bps YoY). Operating income $2.2B (24% margin). EPS $1.20 (+30% YoY).
Revenue ~$9.6B (+/- $300M), up ~25% YoY. Driven by Data Center double-digit seq growth and Embedded returning to growth. Gross Margin ~54.5%.

questions: Managing transition from MI355 to MI400 in 2H 2026?
Visibility into OpenAI engagement and allocation?
answers: Lisa Su: Demand strong into 2026. MI355 ramping 1H 26; sharper ramp in 2H 26 with MI450.
Lisa Su: Planning multiple quarters out for power/supply chain. First gigawatt deploys 2H 26. Good visibility.

questions: Discrete vs System (Helios) sales mix for MI450?
Are components or power the primary constraint for 2026?
answers: Lisa Su: Early MI450 customers focused on rack scale (Helios). Other form factors will follow.
Lisa Su: Industry planning together on power/supply chain. Supply chain is prepared to deliver significant growth.

questions: Sustainability of AI-driven server CPU strength?
Competitiveness of ROCm 7?
answers: Lisa Su: CPU demand durable; AI spawning more general compute needs. Turin ramp fast.
Lisa Su: ROCm 7 significant step forward (Day 0 model support). Customer experience smooth; continuing to invest.

questions: Gross margin framework for MI355 to 400 transition?
Customer breadth beyond OpenAI in 2026/27?
answers: Jean Hu: Margins typically dip during transition then normalize. Priority is top-line/margin dollars.
Lisa Su: Multiple customers expected to reach significant scale with MI450 (OCI, DOE, etc.).

questions: Did Servers or GPUs grow more in Q3?
Clarification on Q4 'strong double digit' guidance?
answers: Jean Hu: Both grew nicely; Server slightly better directionally.
Jean Hu: Sequentially, Data Center up double digits. Both Server and AI contributing.

questions: Has OpenAI deal influenced other customers?
Risk of customer concentration in 2027/28?
answers: Lisa Su: Yes, accelerated interest. Helios at OCP also key.
Lisa Su: Goal is broad customer base. Supply chain dimensioned for multiple large customers.

questions: Server unit vs ASP growth with Turin?
Updated view on $500B AI TAM?
answers: Lisa Su: Turin drives ASPs, but Genoa mix remains strong. Broad-based demand.
Lisa Su: AI Compute TAM going up. Opportunity larger than initial $500B view.

questions: Is OpenAI partnership a tailwind for software stack?
Are CSPs sweating GPUs longer than 5-6 years?
answers: Lisa Su: Yes, large customers strengthen stack. Also using AI to accelerate kernel dev.
Lisa Su: New infra gets latest GPUs (liquid cooled), but older gens (MI300) still widely used for inference.

questions: Posture on MI308 if licenses granted? Readiness?
Do you have inventory?
answers: Lisa Su: Received some licenses. Dynamic situation. No revenue in Q4 guide.
Lisa Su: Have WIP inventory. Will assess demand environment.

questions: How does AMD differentiate to win multi-GW deals?
Was the OpenAI warrant structure unique?
answers: Lisa Su: World needs more compute. MI450 strong product. TCO and open ecosystem key.
Lisa Su: Unique agreement for unique time/scale. Aligned incentives. Open to other creative partnerships.
